data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_0ffc5aee7e62af390069a2901b82c4819080345afcd9870087","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":194,"text":"Foundry Agent Service is Microsoft’s **managed “agent runtime” in Azure AI Foundry/Microsoft Foundry** for building, deploying, and operating AI agents in production—without you having to stitch together conversation state, tool orchestration, safety, identity, and observability on your own. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n\n## What it does (in practical terms)\n- **Manages conversations and state**: You interact with the service using structured conversations; it keeps track of messages and agent activity in a way that’s usable for UIs, debugging, and iteration. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))  \n- **Orchestrates tool calls**: The agent can call tools/actions (e.g., search, data retrieval, functions/connectors) and the service coordinates the calls. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))  \n- **Enterprise readiness**: Built to integrate with **identity, networking, content safety, and observability** so you can move from prototype to production. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))  \n- **Connects to your knowledge and systems**: It’s designed to ground agents on sources like **SharePoint, Microsoft Fabric, Azure AI Search**, and to take actions via a large connector ecosystem (via Logic Apps). ([azure.microsoft.com](https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/products/ai-foundry/agent-service/))\n\n## How you typically use it\n1. Create a **Foundry project** in your Azure subscription and set up the required environment/resources. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/foundry/agents/environment-setup))  \n2. Choose/deploy a model from the Foundry model catalog (the docs commonly reference models like GPT-4-class deployments). ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))  \n3. Build an agent either in the **portal** or using **SDKs** (commonly Python/C#/TypeScript are referenced in materials). ([microsoft.github.io](https://microsoft.github.io/aitour26-WRK540-unlock-your-agents-potential-with-model-context-protocol/agent-service-overview/))  \n4. **Publish** the agent to get a stable endpoint and configure authentication/permissions. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/how-to/publish-agent?view=foundry))  \n\n## “Classic” vs “New” docs (important)\nMicrosoft’s docs note there’s a **classic portal/docs track** and a **newer Foundry experience**, and some quickstarts apply to the older version—so it matters which portal/API surface you’re using. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/overview?view=foundry-classic))\n\n## Related capability: hosted agents (preview)\nIf you have your own agent code/framework and want a managed way to run it, Foundry Agent Service also has **hosted agents** (public preview in the docs), aimed at simplifying containerization, scaling, and ops for agents. ([learn.microsoft.com](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/ai-foundry/agents/concepts/hosted-agents?view=foundry))  \n\nIf you tell me whether you’re using **Azure AI Foundry (new)** or **Foundry classic**, and whether you want **no-code/low-code (portal)** or **code-first (SDK)**, I can point you to the right “getting started” path and the core concepts you’ll hit first."}

